      <h2 id="what-are">What Are Foreclosure Surplus Funds?</h2>
      <p>When a home is sold at a foreclosure auction, the winning bidder pays a price set by the market — not by the lender. In many cases, competitive bidding drives that price above what's needed to pay off the outstanding mortgage, fees, court costs, and any other liens against the property.</p>
      <p>The money left over after all those debts are satisfied is called <strong>foreclosure surplus funds</strong> — also known as <strong>foreclosure overages</strong>, <strong>excess proceeds</strong>, or <strong>surplus proceeds</strong>. By law in every U.S. state, those funds belong to the former homeowner — not the lender, not the county, and not the winning bidder.</p>
      <p>But here's the problem: most former homeowners never find out this money exists. The county court or trustee holds it, sends a legally required notice that often goes unread or gets lost, and waits. If no claim is made by the deadline, the funds are absorbed into the government's general fund — gone forever.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>The key point:</strong> Just because you lost your home to foreclosure doesn't mean you lost all your equity. If the auction price exceeded what you owed, that difference is legally yours — regardless of your credit situation or the circumstances of the foreclosure.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="how-created">How Are Surplus Funds Created?</h2>
      <p>To understand surplus funds, it helps to walk through a typical foreclosure sale:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>The lender files for foreclosure</strong> after the homeowner falls behind on mortgage payments.</li>
        <li><strong>The property is scheduled for auction</strong> — either a courthouse steps sale or online auction, depending on the state.</li>
        <li><strong>Competitive bidding drives up the price.</strong> Investors attend these auctions looking for deals, and multiple bidders often push the final sale price well above what was owed.</li>
        <li><strong>Debts are paid first.</strong> The auction proceeds pay off the mortgage, attorney fees, court costs, and any other recorded liens in priority order.</li>
        <li><strong>The remainder becomes surplus funds.</strong> Whatever is left over after all debts are settled is placed into a court-controlled account, awaiting a claim from the former homeowner.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>For example: imagine you had a $180,000 mortgage remaining when your home went to foreclosure. The auction attracts four competitive bidders and the property ultimately sells for $235,000. After the $180,000 mortgage, $8,000 in attorney and court fees, and a $2,000 HOA lien are paid off, there's $45,000 in surplus funds sitting with the county — legally yours.</p>

      <h2 id="who-eligible">Who Is Eligible to Claim Surplus Funds?</h2>
      <p>In most states, the former homeowner (the person who held title to the property at the time of foreclosure) has first priority to claim surplus funds. This is true even if:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>You voluntarily surrendered the property</li>
        <li>The foreclosure was completed years ago</li>
        <li>You've moved to a different state</li>
        <li>You weren't aware the funds existed</li>
        <li>You had other debts or liens against the property</li>
      </ul>
      <p>In some cases, junior lienholders (such as second mortgage holders or judgment creditors) may also have a right to a portion of the surplus. However, the former homeowner's claim takes priority after secured debts are paid.</p>

      <div class="info-box">
        <h4>📋 What About Tax Sale Surplus Funds?</h4>
        <p>Similar surplus funds are also created when a property is sold at a <strong>tax sale</strong> for unpaid property taxes. If the winning bid at the tax auction exceeds the amount of taxes owed — plus fees and costs — the difference is owed to the former owner. Rightful Returns Recovery handles both types of surplus claims.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="deadlines">How Long Do You Have to Claim?</h2>
      <p>This is the most critical factor — and the most commonly misunderstood. Each state sets its own deadline for claiming foreclosure surplus funds, and these deadlines are strictly enforced. Miss the window and the funds may be permanently lost.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Texas:</strong> 2-year claim window from the date the court issued the order distributing funds</li>
        <li><strong>Georgia:</strong> Up to 5 years in most counties; varies by sale type</li>
        <li><strong>Arizona:</strong> Varies by sale type — judicial vs. trustee sales have different timelines</li>
        <li><strong>Florida:</strong> 60 days from the clerk's notice; then a second 1-year window</li>
        <li><strong>Other states:</strong> Deadlines range from 60 days to several years</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The statute of limitations clock often starts ticking from the date of the foreclosure sale — not the date you received notice, not the date you found out about the funds. This is why acting promptly is so important, even if you're not sure whether funds exist.</p>

      <h2 id="how-to-find">How Do You Find Out If You Have Surplus Funds?</h2>
      <p>There are several ways to search for surplus funds, each with varying degrees of effort and success:</p>
      <h3>Search County Records Yourself</h3>
      <p>Most county clerk of court offices maintain public records of surplus funds. You can visit the courthouse in person, search online court portals (available in some counties), or make a public records request. This process can be time-consuming and requires knowing exactly which county and which case to search.</p>
      <h3>Check Your State's Unclaimed Property Database</h3>
      <p>Some states transfer unclaimed surplus funds to the state comptroller's unclaimed property division after the initial claim window closes. You can search your state's unclaimed property database, though this only catches funds that have already been transferred — not those still in the court's possession.</p>
