      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>Do I need an attorney to claim foreclosure surplus funds?</h4>
        <p>In many states, yes — particularly for judicial foreclosures where the claim must be filed as a court motion. Rightful Returns Recovery works with licensed attorneys in all 50 states and handles all legal filings on your behalf.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>What if I don't remember the details of my foreclosure?</h4>
        <p>That's okay. We search records using your name and former address. You don't need to have your paperwork to start a free search.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>Can I lose my home to foreclosure and still be owed money?</h4>
        <p>Absolutely. The foreclosure extinguished your ownership of the property — but not your right to any equity that existed at the time of sale. If the auction price exceeded your debt, you are owed that difference.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>What if there were multiple liens on my property?</h4>
        <p>Liens are paid in priority order. After secured debts are paid, any remaining surplus goes to the former owner. In some cases other creditors may also file claims, but a professional recovery firm can navigate these situations to maximize what you receive.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>Is foreclosure surplus fund recovery legitimate?</h4>
        <p>Yes. Surplus funds recovery is a legal, established practice recognized in all 50 states. The right of former homeowners to claim excess proceeds is codified in state statutes. Rightful Returns Recovery operates transparently with contingency-only fees — we never charge upfront.</p>
